mong Melanesian societies. This book compares the intent and practice of transcultural psychiatry with Kakoli interpretations of, and responses to, madness, showing the reasons for their occasional recourse to psychiatric services. Episodes involving madness, as defined by the Kakoli themselves, are described in order to offer a context for the historical lifeworld and praxis of the community and raise fundamental questions about whether a culturally sensitive psychiatry is possible in the Melanesian context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aEthnopsychologyzPapua New GuineazWestern Highlands Province. 0aMedical anthropologyzPapua New Guinea. 0aPapuansxMental healthzPapua New GuineazWestern Highlands Province. 0aPapuanszPapua New GuineazWestern Highlands ProvincexMental health. 0aPapuanszPapua New GuineazWestern Highlands ProvincexPsychology. 0aPapuanszPapua New GuineazWestern Highlands ProvincexSocial conditions. 0aPsychiatry, TransculturalzPapua New GuineazWestern Highlands Province. 0aPsychiatry, TransculturalzPapua New Guinea. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745095140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857450951423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857450951/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK